    <h2>SECTION A: Attempt any TWO question.</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>Define state space graph. Differenciate between A* search and greedy best first search.</p>
<p> </p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A <strong><em><span style="text-decoration: underline;">state space graph</span></em></strong> is a set of all possible states that it can reach from the current state. A state space forms a graph in which the nodes are states and the arcs between nodes are actions. The solution of a problem is part of the graph formed by the state space.consists of identifying an INITIAL STATE (from where to begin) and a GOAL STATE (the final destination) and then following a specific sequence of actions (called States).</p>
<p>A solution is a path from initial state to goal state consisting of  set of states,  initial state, operation (which helps to transfer state to its successor state) and goal state.</p>
<p>Example:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone wp-image-36022" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/state-space.drawio.png?resize=217%2C431&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="217" height="431"></p>
<p>Difference between A* and greedy best search is :</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
<tbody>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 24px;"><strong>A* Search</strong></td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 24px;"><strong>Greedy Best Search</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 48px;">
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">The evaluation function for A* search is f(n) = h(n) + g(n).</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">The evaluation function for best-first search is f(n) = h(n).</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 48px;">
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">A* search is optimal as the path found is always optimal.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">Best-first search is not optimal as the path found may not be optimal.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 150px;">
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 150px;">Its time complexity is O(b<sup>m</sup>) and space complexity is also O(b<sup>m</sup>).</p>
<p>where b is the branching and m is the maximum depth of the search tree</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 150px;">Its time complexity is O(b<sup>m</sup>) and space complexity can be polynomial.</p>
<p>where b is the branching and m is the maximum depth of the search tree</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">It requires more memory.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">It requires less memory.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">This search algorithm involves past knowledge.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">This search algorithm does not involve past knowledge.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">It keeps all the nodes in the memory while searching.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; height: 24px;">It keeps all the fringe or border nodes in the memory while searching.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
