<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Differentiate supervised learning from unsupervised? Discuss how Naïve Bayes Model can be used for machine learning ? Support your answer with example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%;">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;"><strong>Unsupervised Learning</strong></td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;"><strong>Supervised Learning</strong></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">Unsupervised Learning is the method of learning by the agents which have no any information about environment.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">Supervised Learning is the method of learning by the agents which have some learning algorithm based on which models are formulated.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">They gain experiences from the environment as inputs and base on the inputs it perform clustering.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">Here, based on previous inputs and outputs experienced, learning algorithms the model gives some output.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">In unsupervised learning there is no any supervisor who have any standard for that task.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">Supervised learning have a supervisor who have some standard for that task.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">Unsupervised learning when gain some amount of data they divide them on the basis of clusters and using K-mean they provide the output.</td>
<td style="width: 50%; text-align: center;">When the new input is given then the difference in the result obtained and the result expected is considered as error .The less the error the precise the learning.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p><strong>Naïve Bayes :</strong></p>
<p>Naïve Bayes is a probabilistic machine learning algorithm used for classification tasks. It’s based on the Bayes Theorem and assumes that features are independent of each other (hence the term “naïve”). Popular applications include spam filtering, document classification, and sentiment prediction<span style="font-size: 13.3333px;">.</span></p>
<p>Bayes Theorem relates conditional probabilities:</p>
<p class="katex-block" style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">A</span><span class="mord">∣</span><span class="mord mathnormal">B</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mrel">=</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">B</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">B</span>∣<span class="mord mathnormal">A</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">⋅</span><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">A</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>In the context of Naïve Bayes:</p>
<p><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">A</span><span class="mord">∣</span><span class="mord mathnormal">B</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span> represents the probability of class A given features B.</p>
<p><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">B</span><span class="mord">∣</span><span class="mord mathnormal">A</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span> is the likelihood of observing features B given class A.</p>
<p><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">A</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span> is the prior probability of class A.</p>
<p><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">B</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></span></span> is the evidence probability of features B.</p>
