<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>What is game search? How minmax search used in game playing ? Illustrate with an example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong> Game search</strong> typically refers to the process of searching through a game tree in order to find the best move or sequence of moves in a game. In this search player main motive is to reach the goal which is best among all by minimizing the oponents move. s typically involves exploring different branches of the tree using techniques such as minimax, alpha-beta pruning etc.</p>
<p><strong>Minmax search</strong> is the search algorithm based on the principle of minimizing the maximum possible loss (hence the name). In a two-player zero-sum game, one player&#8217;s gain is the other player&#8217;s loss. It is a fundamental algorithm used in game-playing. In this algorithm, each node in the tree represents a state of the game, and the edges represent possible moves that can be made from that state.</p>
<p>Levels of the tree operates on alternating , max nodes represent the player whose turn it is and aim to maximize their score while min nodes represent the opponent and aim to minimize the player&#8217;s score. The algorithm recursively explores the game tree, considering all possible moves by both players up to a certain depth or until the game ends. As the algorithm traverses back up the tree, it selects the moves that lead to the highest score for the current player at max nodes and the lowest score at min nodes. These techniques help eliminate branches of the game tree that are known to be worse than previously evaluated branches, reducing the number of nodes that need to be explored.</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone  wp-image-36197 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/05/minmax.drawio.png?resize=720%2C1858&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="720" height="1858"></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
