<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>What is machine vision? Describe the components of machine vision.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><em><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Machine vision</strong></span></em> is a primary component of industrial automation. It is the ability of the computer to see. Explore the diagram above to learn how machine vision system components work together to transform operations. It is one of the founding technologies of industrial automation. It has helped improve product quality, speed production, and optimize manufacturing and logistics for decades.</p>
<p>Machine vision uses cameras to capture visual information from the surrounding environment. It then processes the images using a combination of hardware and software and prepares the information for use in various applications. Components of machine vision are:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong><em>Lens: </em>                                                                                                                             </strong> Lens are placed to capture the image and delivers it to the sensor in the camera as light.</li>
<li><strong><em>Image Processing: </em>                                                                                                   </strong>The processor runs software and related algorithms that process the digital image and extract the required information.</li>
<li><strong><em>Sensor: </em>                                                                                                                         </strong>These devices work together to process the image from the camera and convert it to a digital format as pixels. Image sensors convert light into electric signals.</li>
<li><strong><em>Input /Output hardware:   </em>                                                                                   </strong> I/O devices and hardware are used for input and output for further performance.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>How natural language generation differs from natural language understanding ? How morphological analysisis done in NLP ?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In <strong>Natural language understanding</strong>, computer tries to understand the input provided in natural language where the sentences are broken and understood. Breaking of the sentences to understand them can be of different types and they are syntatic analysis, lexical analysis and referential analysis. Syntatic analysis is the analysis done by breaking the sentences based on the grammetical syntax , lexical analysis  is the analysis done by breaking the sentences into words and referential analysis make the computer understand the refrences of the objects in the sentence.</p>
<p>In<strong> Natural language generating</strong>, computer tries to bind all the knowledge on the basis of its understanding to form back a sentence. It perform test planning where it extract relevent knowledge from the knowledge base. Here the words combines to phases and phases to sentences and so on. Managing of tone , maping of the formalized sentence to provide an output in natural language is done here.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>In general, we can say that Natural language understanding, focuses on breaking the sentences to understand while Natural language generating, focuses on binding all the borken knowledge to re construct a sentence in natural language.</li>
<li>Natural language understanding converts the spoken sentences to broken sentences and knowlegde  whereas Natural language generating converts the formal knowledge into a meningful sentence.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Morphological analysis</strong> is the analysis of the meaning of the words by evaluating the smallest unit of the meaning i.e morpheme. At time of analysis initiallythe morphemes within a word is identified. Prefix and suffix are identified ,this includes determining the grammatical category and the meaning or function of each morpheme within the word. it also includes analyzing inflectional morphology, which involves the modification of words to indicate grammatical features such as tense, aspect, mood, number, gender, case, and person.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><em>Tense</em></span> : In tense morphological analysis is as :</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;">Drive (v<sub>1</sub> ) + ing = Driving (v<sub>4</sub> )</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><em><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Singular/plural</span> </em>: In Singular/plural morphological analysis can be done as :</li>
</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;">Bus (Singular) + es  = Buses (Plural)</p>
<p>Morphological analysis has various applications in linguistics, natural language processing, and language learning. Morphological analysis provides valuable insights into the structure and meaning of words in a language, helping to understand how words are formed, how they convey meaning, and how they are used grammatically.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>What is constraint satisfaction problem? Illustrate graph coloring problem as constraint satisfaction problem.</p>
<p> </p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A Constraint Satisfaction Problem (CSP) is a computational problem where the goal is to find a solution that satisfies a set of constraints.  Finding values for a group of variables that fulfill a set of restrictions or rules is the aim of constraint satisfaction problems.  These problems arise in various fields, including resource allocation, planning, scheduling, and decision-making. A Constraint Satisfaction Problem (CSP) consist of a set of variable, a domain value and set of constraints</p>
<p>It is usually represented as an undirected graph called constraint graph where the nodes are the variables and the edges are the binary constraints.</p>
</div>
</body></html>